		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Chivalry</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Chivalry_(disambiguation)" title="Chivalry (disambiguation)">Chivalry (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="rellink boilerplate seealso">See also: <a href="/wiki/Chivalric_order" title="Chivalric order">Chivalric order</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Bors_and_Lionel.jpg" class="image" title="Bors' Dilemma - he chooses to save a maiden rather than his brother Lionel."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Bors_and_Lionel.jpg/300px-Bors_and_Lionel.jpg" width="300" height="196" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Bors_and_Lionel.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Bors" title="Bors">Bors</a>' Dilemma - he chooses to save a maiden rather than his brother <a href="/wiki/Sir_Lionel" title="Sir Lionel">Lionel</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Chivalry</b> is a term relating to the <a href="/wiki/Medieval" title="Medieval" class="mw-redirect">medieval</a> institution of <a href="/wiki/Knighthood" title="Knighthood" class="mw-redirect">knighthood</a>. It is usually associated with ideals of <a href="/wiki/Knightly_virtues" title="Knightly virtues" class="mw-redirect">knightly virtues</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honor" title="Honor" class="mw-redirect">honor</a> and <a href="/wiki/Courtly_love" title="Courtly love">courtly love</a>. Today, the terms <i>chivalry</i> and <i>chivalrous</i> are used to describe courteous behavior, especially that of men towards women.</p>
